I think there's no reason `Q` can't be in an arbitrary universe; the test objects `X` and `Y` need to be in the universe of `R` (or higher, but Module.Baer is purely in the universe of `R`), but `Q` need not be. There's no similar restriction for Module.Projective, and the restriction seems to have [made it hard to use](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Universe.20trouble.20when.20using.20.60.60.60Module.2EInjective.60.60.60/near/403006687). Can you address this issue as well?

It's an interesting question to ponder whether it suffices to use test objects in the same universe as `Q`; I haven't been able to come up with counterexamples or proof.

Another thought is that we may switch a design similar to [IntermediateField.Lifts](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/FieldTheory/Adjoin.html#IntermediateField.Lifts) instead of LinearPMap for the proof of Baer's criterion. Maybe we could have an unified API for extension of homomorphisms algebraic structures, depending on how often such proofs come up. But that's definitely for another PR ...

For the universe problem, I tried 3 things

1. Test object in higher universe:
```lean
class Module.Injective : Prop where
  out : âˆ€ â¦ƒX Y : Type max u vâ¦„ [AddCommGroup X] [AddCommGroup Y] [Module R X] [Module R Y]
    (f : X â†’â‚—[R] Y) (_ : Function.Injective f) (g : X â†’â‚—[R] Q),
    âˆƒ h : Y â†’â‚—[R] Q, âˆ€ x, h (f x) = g x
```

```lean
theorem Module.injective_object_of_injective_module [inj : Module.Injective R Q] :
    CategoryTheory.Injective (ModuleCat.of R Q) where
  factors {X Y} g f m := by
    let f' : ULift.{max u v} X â†’â‚—[R] ULift.{max u v} Y :=
      ULift.moduleEquiv.symm.toLinearMap âˆ˜â‚— f âˆ˜â‚— ULift.moduleEquiv.toLinearMap
    have hf' : Function.Injective f' := ULift.up_injective.comp <|
      (ModuleCat.mono_iff_injective _).mp m |>.comp ULift.down_injective
    let g' : ULift.{max u v} X â†’â‚—[R] Q := g âˆ˜â‚— ULift.moduleEquiv.toLinearMap
    obtain âŸ¨l, hâŸ© := inj.out f' hf' g'
    exact âŸ¨l âˆ˜â‚— ULift.moduleEquiv.symm.toLinearMap, LinearMap.ext fun x â†¦ by aesopâŸ©
```
is doable by playing with `ULift.moduleEquiv`, but
```lean
theorem Module.injective_module_of_injective_object
    [inj : CategoryTheory.Injective <| ModuleCat.of R Q] :
    Module.Injective R Q where
  out X Y _ _ _ _ f hf g := by
    have H := @CategoryTheory.Injective.factors (self := inj)
    sorry
```
seems not to be possible because `X, Y` are in universe `max u v` but `H` want universe modules to be in universe `v`


2. `Q, X, Y` all in the same universe

```lean
class Module.Injective : Prop where
  out : âˆ€ â¦ƒX Y : Type vâ¦„ [AddCommGroup X] [AddCommGroup Y] [Module R X] [Module R Y]
    (f : X â†’â‚—[R] Y) (_ : Function.Injective f) (g : X â†’â‚—[R] Q),
    âˆƒ h : Y â†’â‚—[R] Q, âˆ€ x, h (f x) = g x
```
is fine up until `Module.Baer.of_injective` because ideals are in universe `u` and can't be easily transferred to `v`.

3. use `[UnivLE.{u, v}]` to solve the problem in the second approach, now we can `Shrink I` to make an object in universe `v`, I don't know if this makes the universes easier to use though

I think your solution 1 is probably the best for now; you can have a version of `Module.injective_module_of_injective_object` that uses `ModuleCat.of R (ULift Q)` and another version that requires `Q : TypeMax`.

In [9e067bb](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905/commits/9e067bb375f91e015774651c4f725f89b5956be5), I made a version of solution 3, it is actually quite smooth (universe level doesn't need to be specifically spelt out anymore). Does this change your preference of solution 1?
It doesn't build yet? Is it really solution 3, I don't see any UnivLE in it?

I forgot to push and quoted the wrong commit. The correct one is [10a89bc](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905/commits/10a89bc7b4794ae0a4ccb210f31c1f3ea7bbcb82) :laughing:. It builds up to `section ulift` (lifting injective modules to higher universes), I will do this section tomorrow.
The full version using `UnivLE` is in [0ce04e6](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905/commits/0ce04e69b49037aea05fa7b13dff8d6d70237deb)

I really think `Module.injective_module_iff_injective_object` being a provable statement without lifting `Q` should be a consideration when assessing what the correct `Module.Injective` version should be.
I agree! See https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905#discussion_r1428509361 for some ideas.
This can now be removed.
Indeed, the `Mathlib.Data.TypeMax`  should be okay to remove as well. Thanks!
This proof has got a lot longer, and isn't UnivLE supposed to make things easier? What's going on here?

`UnivLE` make proof easier in the sense that less universe variable need to be made explicit. The length is longer because of `I` can't be lifted using `ULift` any more but need to use `Shrink I` whose instances needs to be manually introduced via bijection `I \equiv Shrink I`. But the idea of the proof is the same. 

I guess one way of making this proof roughly the same as before is to introduce `LinearlyShrink R M` as a type alias of `Shrink M` for `R`-modules and put default instances and update `equivShrink` to a linear equivalence (also do the same for groups, rings, algebras etc). But maybe for another PR if others think this is a good idea. @alreadydone what do you think about this idea?
See [this](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Universe.20trouble.20when.20using.20.60.60.60Module.2EInjective.60.60.60/near/403006687) problem

I think you can put AddCommGroup and Module structures on `Shrink I` just like [ULift.module'](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Module/ULift.html#ULift.module') and then construct a LinearEquiv between `I` and `Shrink I` in parallel to [ULift.moduleEquiv](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Module/ULift.html#ULift.moduleEquiv), which you can then compose with the linear maps involved here.

It's unfortunate that we have to duplicate the ULift API; if [lean4#2297](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/pull/2297) could be solved we wouldn't need to open the UnivLE business ... (if you want to see it happen please upvote)
I did this in [634f566](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905/commits/634f56646d69d5e68a4b821f9430167479b05786), but I think this should be a separate PR
Now the proof of this lemma is about the same size!
`max v`?
This is a typo, I didn't know Lean allows this
`variable {M : Type v} [AddCommGroup M] [Module R M]` could be extracted from this and the following.
done

```suggestion
variable {M : Type v} [AddCommGroup M] [Module R M]
```

I have concerns about this aberration from the design of Module.Projective. There we use a test object in a higher universe (a free module generated by elements of the module): the advantage is we get the lifting property in arbitrary universes [Module.projective_lifting_property](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Module/Projective.html#Module.projective_lifting_property), but the cost is that [IsProjective.iff_projective](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Category/ModuleCat/Projective.html#IsProjective.iff_projective) (what a weird name!) only holds in module universes no lower than the ring.

Your [solution 1](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905#discussion_r1421608548) would be conforming to a similar design. But now you're adopting a definition of Module.Injective that uses only test objects in the same universe, so you only have the extension property in the same universe but not the higher universes, but the good thing is that [Module.injective_iff_injective_object](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Module/Injective.html#Module.injective_iff_injective_object) holds in any universe. (By the way, it's probably more convenient to state the fully universe-polymorphic extension property assuming Module.Baer (), which will be easier to use than Category.Injective of the ULifts.)

I think the Projective design is reasonable because people are probably most interested in the full lifting property rather than the version restricted to one universe, but I can't say your choice is definitely worse. Of course, if we could prove the extension property in the same universe implies the fully-polymorphic one, we won't need to worry about this. I have some ideas about this: firstly `I â†’ Q` in the Baer condition can be replaced by an injective linear map `I/ker â†’ Q`, so that `#(I/ker) â‰¤ #Q`, but it's not necessary that `#(R/ker) â‰¤ #Q`. Secondly maybe we can somehow "replace" `R` by `R/ann(Q)` where `ann(Q)` is the two sided ideal that sends every element of Q to 0 (so `R/ann(Q)` acts faithfully and has cardinality at most `#Q^#Q`), but I can't quite obtain an injective linear map `I/J â†’ R/ann(Q)` such that `I â†’ Q` factors through `I/J`; that requires `I âŠ“ ann(Q) â‰¤ J` and `J â‰¤ ker` but we only have `ann(Q) * I â‰¤ ker`. Thirdly I'm now looking into injective hulls, and hopefully something has been said about their cardinalities.

```lean

universe uR uM uP uP'

variable [UnivLE.{uR, uM}]
variable (R : Type uR) [Ring R]
variable (M : Type uM) [AddCommGroup M] [Module R M] [inj : Module.Injective R M]
variable (P : Type uP) [AddCommGroup P] [Module R P]
variable (P' : Type uP') [AddCommGroup P'] [Module R P']

lemma Module.Injective.lifting_property
    (f : P â†’â‚—[R] P') (hf : Function.Injective f)
    (g : P â†’â‚—[R] M) : âˆƒ h : P' â†’â‚—[R] M, h âˆ˜â‚— f = g := by
  have inj' : Module.Injective R (ULift.{max uM uP uP'} M) :=
    Module.ulift_injective_of_injective.{uR, uM, max uM uP uP'} R inj
  obtain âŸ¨h, HâŸ© := inj'.out
    (ULift.moduleEquiv.symm.toLinearMap âˆ˜â‚— f âˆ˜â‚— ULift.moduleEquiv.toLinearMap :
      ULift.{max uM uP uP'} P â†’â‚—[R] ULift.{max uM uP uP'} P')
    (ULift.moduleEquiv.symm.injective.comp (hf.comp ULift.moduleEquiv.injective))
    (ULift.moduleEquiv.symm.toLinearMap âˆ˜â‚— g âˆ˜â‚— ULift.moduleEquiv.toLinearMap)
  refine âŸ¨ULift.moduleEquiv.toLinearMap âˆ˜â‚— h âˆ˜â‚— ULift.moduleEquiv.symm.toLinearMap, ?_âŸ©
  ext x
  specialize H (ULift.up x)
  simp only [LinearMap.coe_comp, LinearEquiv.coe_coe, Function.comp_apply, ULift.moduleEquiv_apply,
    ULift.moduleEquiv_symm_apply] at H âŠ¢
  rw [H]
```
This is the best result in terms of universe polymorphism I can get using `UnivLE`
I didn't quite follow your proof, which linear map are we taking `ker`
Yeah that's what I have in mind too. But it should be called extension_property not lifting. Also, you could prove Module.Baer.extension_property without UnivLE.
`Module.Baer.extension_property` has been added (fully universally polymorphic, maybe like you suggested, `Module.Baer` should be the definitoin of `Module.Injective`

That's great!

> I didn't quite follow your proof, which linear map are we taking ker

Just saw this. I mean the kernel of I â†’ Q. You can replace `I â†’ R` by `I/ker â†’ R/ker` but you don't have info about the cardinality of `R/ker`. But there's freedom to replace `R/ker` by `R/J` with `J` such that `J âŠ“ I = ker`, so that `I/ker â†’ R/J` stays injective (as required in the extension property).

Anyway I'm now convinced whether we can test Q with objects in the same universe is equivalent to whether Q's R-injective hull (or rather its cardinality) lies in the same universe. So I really need to look into the construction of injective hulls ... (On the dual side, a projective cover may not exist, but a flat cover always does!)

Update: I'm almost sure that being an injective module in a universe lower than the ring's universe doesn't imply being injective in the ring's universe (equivalently, Module.Baer). For details, see [this comment](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9120/files#r1509525127). Correct link: https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9120#discussion_r1509525127

I think the proofs should just work, but let me know if not.
```suggestion
variable {R Q} {M N : Type*} [AddCommGroup M] [AddCommGroup N]
```
This works Thanks

These should say `Ulift.{v}` instead of `ULift.{max v v'}`, and the second doesn't require UnivLE. See [my branch](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/compare/zjj/liftInjectiveModules...jyxu/liftInjectiveModules?expand=1).
This is golfed via Module.Baer in my branch.
Thanks for all the golfing
